out 1261":"about 1261","about 1270":"about 1270","1220":"1220","1263":"1263","1240":"1240","1261":"1261","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1258":"1258","1225":"1225","1245":"1245","1267":"1267","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","Dalry, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Dalry, Ayrshire, Scotland","England":"England","Dalry, North Ayrshire, Scotland,":"Dalry, North Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lynn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhloinn</b> and <b>Ó Fhloinn</b> (see   Flynn  ).","Scottish: variant of   Lyne   3.","English: habitational name from any of several places so called in Norfolk, in particular King's Lynn, an important center of the medieval wool trade. The placename is probably from an Old Welsh word cognate with Gaelic <i>linn</i> ‘pool, stream’."],"variants":[{"name":"Lyn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Ding, Fatt, Tov, Yol, Yun.","Scottish and English: variant of   Lynn  .","Probably also an altered form of Dutch <b>Van der Lijn</b> (see   Vanderlinden  )."]},{"name":"Linn","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Lynn  .","German: habitational name from a place called Linn, named with <i>lin</i> ‘swamp, bog, marsh’.","German: from an ancient Germanic personal name, <i>Linto</i>, formed with Old High German <i>lind(i)</i> ‘soft’."]},{"name":"Lenn","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Lynn  .","Jewish(Ashkenazic): variant of   Len  ."]},{"name":"Flynn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Connor, Declan, Kieran, Aidan, Brigid, Cathal, Dermot, Donal, Eamon, John Patrick, Kiernan.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Floinn</b> ‘descendant of <i>Flann</i>’, a byname meaning ‘red(dish), ruddy’. There were families of this name in various parts of Ireland. This name has also been Anglicized as   Lindsay  .","English: from Middle English <i>Flin</i>, representing the Old Norse male personal name <i>Fleinn</i>."]},{"name":"Lynne","meanings":["Scottish or English: variant of   Lynn  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Lynn was born in 1245, in Dalry, Ayrshire, Scotland, his father, Walter De Lynn, was 25 and his mother, De Lynn, was 20. He married De Lynn in 1258, in England. They were the parents of at least 5 sons and 2 daughters."},"et":{"1245–":"1245–Surnud","1245–Male":"1245–Surnud","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1258–1310":"1258–1310","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1261–Female":"1261–Surnud","1263–Male":"1263–Surnud","1267–Male":"1267–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1225–Female":"1225–Surnud","about 1260":"umbes 1260","about 1261":"umbes 1261","about 1270":"umbes 1270","1220":"1220","1263":"1263","1240":"1240","1261":"1261","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1258":"1258","1225":"1225","1245":"1245","1267":"1267","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","Dalry, A